post_text:
Parents and Students - I am working daily to communicate with the Texas Education Agency and our local health organizations to make decisions on the course of action we will take. At this time, there is not any data/information reported that would cause us to make any decisions about prolonging Spring Break or closing the campus for a longer amount of time.
We all know things are changing daily and when/if there is reason for us to make a decision, we will let you know as soon as possible. I do believe that there is a strong possibility we will be making changes to the school calendar and how we handle our educational services at some point but for today, that decision has not been made.
In the meantime, we are busy planning for any and all contingencies to be prepared for school closure following the guidelines provided to us by state and federal agencies.
Please do your best to stay home and follow recommendations for social distancing. I will continue to keep you informed in the coming days.
Melissa Pardue, Superintendent

post_text: The horticulture class at Ranch Academy has been actively volunteering for Free Earth Project, a local non-profit. This is our second year working with them. Last year we helped seed all of their starter trays, paint the row signs and a few students helped mulch the main garden beds. So far this year horticulture has planted a bed of garlic bulbs and a bed of onions that will be donated to families in need. We are so proud to be a part of something that gives back to our community! ♥️

post_text: As colder weather approaches, I want to remind everyone that we make a decision about late opening or school closure as early as possible when we know that inclement weather could cause road conditions to be unsafe to travel. We take every precaution to keep our staff and students safe so please know if we don’t alter school due to weather conditions, it should be safe for driving to attend school. Please check this page, our website or message a staff member if in doubt about coming to school. It will be posted here and the students are aware of this. If we don’t open late or close, students are expected to be at school. Thank you!

post_text:
This Friday, November 15th, we will be hosting our 2nd annual bonfire. This event is open to current 2019-2020 students and families. The bonfire will begin at 2:30 on the hill and run until 5:30. We will be providing hot dogs, buns and chili.

The female students are asked to bring either a dessert or chips and male students are asked to bring canned drinks to school Friday morning. No open container yeti/styrofoam/tumbler type drinks will be allowed. Bring your lawn chairs and let's have some fun!

post_text: Today is National Suicide Prevention Day. Love on someone who might be suffering. Reach out if you feel alone and need help. We are here. ♥️
shared_text:
Special Books by Special Kids
September 10, 2019 at 10:12 AM ·

It is with intention that I shared Daniel's interview yesterday. Today is National Suicide Prevention day. Daniel admitted that he felt hopeless and did not see a future. Still, he decided to seek treatment. He told me that his hope was that his interview would inspire others to do the same. Seeking help when you need it is the ultimate sign of strength and courage. You will be rewarded with love and gratitude for reaching out. Don't suffer in silence. Let's all take a page from Daniel today. There is always a tomorrow.

post_text:
Last week we were honored to be invited to see a former student, Casey Bass, receive a 32,000 scholarship! He personally came to the school from Sulfur Springs to extend the invitation and express to us how much of an impact we made on him during his time at Ranch Academy. The night was filled with tears and laughter as we reminisced over meaningful and funny moments. We got to meet others that made a significant impact on him like his guidance counselor, childhood best friend and family.

It was a night we will not forget! We are SO PROUD of you Casey. Now show the world who you are!

🖤 Friday Events:

▪️Girl's Lock in:

▪️Arrive at school between 6:00 & 6:30 P.M.

▪️We will provide pizza for dinner and then activities and movies that night. Girls need to be picked up @ 9:00 A.M.

▪️Bring:
▪️Pillow/sleeping bag or blanket
▪️Pajamas or sweats
▪️Makeup, fingernail polish, movie to share with group- if they have any of these items.
▪️$5 for dinner/breakfast
▪️One show and tell item to share something personal/deep/interesting about themselves

▪️Boy's Friday Fun:

▪️What's Up Fun Park located at 700 East Cedar Parkway in Seven Points

▪️Boys can either drive themselves or ride with a staff chaperone. We are not allowing students to ride with other students for this trip.

▪️Boys need $25 for admission. The school is providing dinner. If someone wants to play paintball, it is $10 extra.

▪️You can pick up your child at the school at 9:30 P.M. If you prefer to pick your child up at What's Up, please let us know!

post_text: Ms. Johnson's art class is creating replicas of Pablo Picasso's works this week. 🎨 They watched an interesting documentary that explained some of the inspiration behind his pieces and style. The kids are all pretty into it because his style is less intimidating to replicate since he uses a wide range of colors & patterns and he distorts body & facial structures. We will post finals of their pieces soon!

The Seniors got us yesterday! 💥 Blair's office got trashed and Ms. J's car got wrapped! Mr. Blair has an unshakable poker face though so he pranked them right back. I really though a few of them might cry for a second. The way he ended his "reprimand" was great!

* Mr. Blair, "You THINK this is funny?!"
* Students, "No, sir."
* Mr. Blair, " Well, I do."

💙 Happy Friday from the Phoenixes!

post_text: 🌱🌱🌱 Horticulture class started planting some of the early crops for the Free Earth Project. They can't wait for the season to start so they can learn about transplanting and get all of these babies in the ground! This is just the first batch of starts. Onions, shallots, eggplant, asparagus, artichokes, basil, lavender, rosemary, tarragon, thyme, dill, cilantro, chamomile, sage, chives, marjoram, spearmint, oregano, phlox, snap dragon, pansies, columbines, and vincas. The students will eventually get to take a trip to see the fruits of their labor! 🌎

📢📢📢 Every year Ranch Academy hosts a food drive for a family in need and the time has come again!
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
🌽🍗🥕 This week, through Friday, we will be accepting non-perishable food items for our food drive. (Yes, I know those emojis are perishable, there are no cans.🤷‍♀️)

📢📢📢 Please send them with your kiddos in the mornings (we will have a bin in the cafeteria for them to put food in) or parents can deliver it to the front desk to Brittany.

🍿🥜🥘 Think outside the box as well...we like to be able to provide food for the whole week as the kids will be home from school all day-not just for Thanksgiving dinner. Thank you so much for everything you do and don't forget Friday is early release!!!

post_text: Yesterday was a beautiful day. Since Earth Day fell on a Saturday this year and we wanted students involved, we instead choose yesterday to honor the planet. Our Earth Day project was building a bee garden, fit with flowers that bees love and little bee homes. We have much work to do but we are so thrilled with the progress. A very big thank you to all of the students who helped Mr. Robson, Ms. Johnson and Mr. RJ tackle this enormous project. We appreciate every single one of you! We have much more work to do in the garden and we'll be sharing our progress as we go along!

post_text:
Presidents’ Day was established in 1885 in honor of George Washington, whose birthday fell on February 22nd. Originally falling on Washington’s actual birth date each year, Presidents’ Day was moved to the third Monday in February as a part of the 1971 Uniform Monday Holiday Act, which was established to create more three-day weekends for workers. (YAY!)

According to the federal government, the holiday’s official name is still “Washington’s Birthday," and on February 22nd each year, Washington’s farewell address is still read in the United States Senate.

Have a great holiday and stay safe! We will see the Phoenixes back on Tuesday the 20th!

post_text: School will be closed on Tuesday, February 7th and will re-open Wednesday morning. Due to increased illness over the past several school days, we will close to disinfect/sanitize all surfaces and allow the students time to recover. There seems to be a stomach bug jumping around so hopefully a 24 hour downtime will help clear it out! Thank you!

post_text:
This conference has been highly motivating and refreshing. We had the opportunity to network and meet other educators, listen to incredible stories of transformation and let loose with some down to earth folks.
The man pictured is Aric Bostic. Check out his website aricbostic.com and take the time to learn his story and absorb his energy, you won't regret it.
BE WHERE YOUR FEET ARE.
